19. JMS / Kafka
Do you have experience with JMS / Kafka: Yes, I have used them to build decoupled, event-driven systems.
What is the purpose of JMS: To provide a common Java API for creating, sending, and receiving messages between distributed systems.
Difference between topic and queue: A Queue is Point-to-Point (one message = one consumer); a Topic is Publish/Subscribe (one message = many consumers).
What are message selectors? How do they work: They are SQL92-like expressions that allow a consumer to filter which messages it wants to receive based on header/property values.
What means message durability and how to achieve it: It ensures messages are not lost if the broker crashes; achieved by marking messages as "Persistent" and using "Durable Subscriptions" in Topics.
What are the different types of messages available in the JMS API: TextMessage, MapMessage, BytesMessage, ObjectMessage, and StreamMessage.
Kafka: Describe an Offset: A unique, sequential integer ID assigned to each message within a partition that marks the consumer's position.
Kafka: What are advantages and significance of Kafka technology: High throughput, massive scalability, fault tolerance, and message durability (messages are stored on disk).
Kafka: What is a partitioning key: A value (like userId) sent with a message to ensure all messages with that key go to the same partition, preserving order.
Kafka: How to ensure message uniqueness: Use an Idempotent Producer by setting enable.idempotence=true, which prevents duplicates during retries.
Kafka: Is it possible to get the message offset after producing: Yes; the RecordMetadata returned by the send() method contains the offset of the message.

Purpose of JMS: JMS is a standard Java API that provides a common way for Java applications to create, send, receive, and read messages. It enables asynchronous, reliable, and loosely coupled communication between distributed software components, abstracting the vendor-specific details of different message-oriented middleware (MOM) providers.
Difference Between Topic and Queue:
Queue (Point-to-Point): A message is sent to exactly one consumer. The queue holds the message until it is consumed or expires. If multiple consumers are listening, only one will receive any given message (load balancing).
Topic (Publish/Subscribe): A message is broadcast to all active subscribers. Each subscriber receives its own copy of the message. If no one is subscribed, the message is typically lost unless durable subscriptions are used.
Message Selectors: These are SQL92-based conditional strings used by consumers to filter messages based on header and property values. The JMS provider performs the filtering before delivery.
Note: Selectors cannot filter based on the message body.
Message Durability: This refers to a subscriber's ability to receive messages that were published while it was offline.
How to achieve it: Use session.createDurableSubscriber(topic, name) for Topic-based messaging. For the message itself to survive a broker crash, it must be set to DeliveryMode.PERSISTENT.
JMS Message Types:
TextMessage: Contains a java.lang.String (often used for XML or JSON).
MapMessage: A set of name/value pairs.
BytesMessage: A stream of uninterpreted bytes.
StreamMessage: A stream of Java primitive types read sequentially.
ObjectMessage: A serialized Java object.
Apache Kafka
Description of an Offset: An offset is a unique, sequential integer ID assigned to each message within a partition. It acts as a cursor, allowing consumers to track their progress and "rewind" to re-read older data if needed.
Advantages and Significance:
High Throughput: Optimized for millions of messages per second.
Scalability: Uses partitioning to distribute data across multiple brokers.
Durability: Messages are persisted to disk and replicated across the cluster for fault tolerance.
Replayability: Consumers can read historical data at their own pace.
Partitioning Key: A key used by the producer to determine which partition a message is sent to. Messages with the same key are guaranteed to be sent to the same partition, ensuring strict ordering for that key.
Message Uniqueness (Idempotence): To ensure a message is processed exactly once (uniqueness), enable the idempotent producer by setting enable.idempotence=true. This prevents duplicates caused by network retries by assigning each producer a unique ID and sequence numbers for every message.
Getting the Offset After Producing: Yes, you can retrieve the offset from the RecordMetadata object returned by the send() method.


