SQL & Database Management Systems
Experience with SQL: I am highly proficient in SQL (Standard/ANSI) and its vendor-specific dialects such as PL/SQL (Oracle), T-SQL (SQL Server), and PostgresSQL.
DML vs. DDL:
DDL (Data Definition Language): Defines the database structure (schema). Commands: CREATE, ALTER, DROP, TRUNCATE.
DML (Data Manipulation Language): Manages the data within the schema. Commands: SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE.
Aggregate Functions: Functions that perform a calculation on a set of values and return a single value.
COUNT(): Counts rows.
SUM(): Adds values.
AVG(): Calculates average.
MAX() / MIN(): Finds highest/lowest values.
Primary Key vs. Unique Key:
Primary Key: Uniquely identifies a record. Cannot be NULL. Only one per table.
Unique Key: Ensures all values in a column are unique. Can accept one NULL value (in most DBs). Multiple unique keys allowed per table.
Transactions: A logical unit of work that contains one or more SQL statements. It follows the "all or nothing" principle—either all changes are saved (COMMIT) or all are undone (ROLLBACK).
ACID Properties:
Atomicity: Transaction is "all or nothing."
Consistency: Database moves from one valid state to another.
Isolation: Transactions don't interfere with each other.
Durability: Once committed, changes survive system failures.
Views & Materialized Views:
View: A "virtual table" based on a stored query. Used for security (hiding columns) and simplifying complex joins. It does not store data.
Materialized View: Stores the result set on disk. Used for performance on heavy calculations; needs periodic refreshing.
Constraints: Rules enforced on data columns.
NOT NULL, UNIQUE, PRIMARY KEY, FOREIGN KEY, CHECK, DEFAULT.
Database Indexes:
Role: A data structure (usually a B-Tree) that speeds up data retrieval.
Analogy: Like an index at the back of a book; it allows the DB to find rows without scanning the entire table (Full Table Scan).
Joins:
INNER JOIN: Returns records with matching values in both tables.
LEFT/RIGHT OUTER JOIN: Returns all records from one table and the matched records from the other (unmatched side returns NULL).
FULL OUTER JOIN: Returns all records when there is a match in either table.
CROSS JOIN: Cartesian product (every row with every row).
Index Performance Trade-off:
Why many indexes are bad: While they speed up SELECT, they slow down INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE because the database must update the index structure every time the data changes.
Most affected command: INSERT is significantly affected as every index on the table must be updated for the new row.
Transaction Isolation Levels:
Read Uncommitted: Lowest level, allows "dirty reads."
Read Committed: Prevents dirty reads (Default for most).
Repeatable Read: Prevents non-repeatable reads.
Serializable: Highest level; prevents "phantom reads" by simulating serial execution.
Types of Tables:
Regular (Heap): Data stored in no particular order.
Temporary: Data exists only for the duration of a session/transaction.
Index-Organized (IOT): Data is stored inside the B-Tree of the Primary Key (rows are physically sorted).
Normalization vs. De-normalization:
Normalization: Organizing data to reduce redundancy (using 1NF, 2NF, 3NF).
De-normalization: Intentionally adding redundancy to a normalized database to improve read performance (reducing the number of joins).
Increasing DB Performance:
Indexing, Partitioning, Query Optimization (EXPLAIN PLAN), Caching, Hardware Scaling (Vertical/Horizontal), and Database Sharding.
SQL vs. NoSQL:
SQL: Relational, structured (tables/rows), predefined schema, scales vertically.
NoSQL: Non-relational, flexible schema (Document, Key-Value, Graph), scales horizontally (distributed).
SQL Standard Implementation: No. While they follow the ANSI standard, every vendor (Oracle, MySQL, Postgres) has its own extensions and slight variations in syntax.
