Detailed Pattern Explanations
Bridge vs. Adapter
Adapter: Converts the interface of a class into another interface clients expect. It makes incompatible interfaces work together (e.g., a "Square" object working in a "Circle" slot).
Bridge: Decouples an abstraction from its implementation so the two can vary independently. It uses composition over inheritance to avoid a "class explosion."
Flyweight Pattern
Used to minimize memory usage by sharing as much data as possible with similar objects. It is ideal when you have thousands of small objects (e.g., characters in a word processor).
Example: Java’s Integer.valueOf(int) caches values between -128 and 127.
Builder Pattern
Separates the construction of a complex object from its representation. It allows you to produce different types and representations of an object using the same construction code.
Key Advantage: Avoids "Telescoping Constructors" (constructors with too many parameters).
Key Comparisons
Comparison	Key Difference
Abstract Factory vs. Builder	Factory focuses on what is created (returns the object in one shot). Builder focuses on how it's created (step-by-step construction).
Adapter vs. Decorator	Adapter changes the interface to make it compatible. Decorator enhances the behavior but keeps the same interface.
