Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) & Design
Inheritance vs. Composition:
Inheritance ("is-a"): A class derives from a parent class (e.g., Car extends Vehicle). It allows for polymorphism but creates tight coupling. Changes in the parent often break the child.
Composition ("has-a"): A class holds an instance of another class as a field (e.g., Car has an Engine). This is flexible and follows the principle of "Favor composition over inheritance," as it allows behavior to be swapped at runtime.
OOD Principles: Beyond SOLID, common principles include DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself), KISS (Keep It Simple, Stupid), Y-AGNI (You Ain't Gonna Need It), and Encapsulate what varies.
Coupling & Cohesion:
Cohesion: How focused a single module/class is. High Cohesion is good; it means the class does one thing and does it well.
Coupling: How dependent modules are on each other. Low Coupling is good; it means changes in one module don't force changes in others.
SOLID Principles
The SOLID principles are five design guidelines intended to make software designs more understandable, flexible, and maintainable.
✅ S - Single Responsibility Principle (SRP): A class should have one, and only one, reason to change. It should perform only one specific task or represent one specific concept.
✅ O - Open/Closed Principle (OCP): Software entities (classes, modules, functions) should be open for extension but closed for modification. You should be able to add new functionality without changing existing code.
✅ L - Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP): Objects of a superclass should be replaceable with objects of its subclasses without breaking the application. Subclasses must honor the "contract" of the parent.
✅ I - Interface Segregation Principle (ISP): Clients should not be forced to depend on methods they do not use. It is better to have many specific interfaces than one large "fat" interface.
✅ D - Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP): Depend on abstractions, not concretions. High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules; both should depend on interfaces.
Detailed Insight: Dependency Inversion (DIP)
How it works: Instead of a Switch class directly instantiating a LightBulb class, both should depend on an IsSwitchable interface.
Why it matters: This allows you to swap the LightBulb for a Fan or a Television without ever modifying the Switch code. It is the foundation for Dependency Injection in frameworks like Spring.



