Foundations: Threads & Execution
Thread vs. Runnable:
Thread is a class; Runnable is a functional interface.
Using Runnable is preferred because it separates the task from the runner and allows your class to extend another class (since Java doesn't support multiple inheritance).
run() vs. start():
Calling run() is just a normal method call in the current thread.
Calling start() requests the JVM to create a new OS-level thread, which then executes the run() method.
Execution Order: There is no guaranteed order of execution in multithreading. The OS thread scheduler decides which thread runs when. Never write code that assumes Thread A will finish before Thread B without explicit synchronization.
Synchronization & Communication
Blocks vs. Methods:
synchronized methods lock the entire object (this).
synchronized blocks allow for "fine-grained" locking, where you only lock a specific object or a critical section of code, improving performance.
wait() / notify(): Used for inter-thread communication. A thread calls wait() to give up the lock and go to sleep until another thread calls notify() or notifyAll() on that same object to wake it up.
Sleep vs. Wait:
Thread.sleep(): Keeps the lock; used for pausing execution.
Object.wait(): Releases the lock; used for coordination.
Memory & Visibility
Volatile: Ensures that a variable is always read from and written to main memory, not a thread's local cache. It guarantees visibility (all threads see the latest value) but does not guarantee atomicity (e.g., i++ is not safe with volatile).
Atomic Operations: Operations that happen all at once or not at all. In Java, java.util.concurrent.atomic classes (like AtomicInteger) use CAS (Compare-And-Swap) to update values without using heavy locks.
Atomicity of Long/Double: On 32-bit JVMs, assigning a 64-bit long or double is actually two 32-bit operations. This can lead to "word tearing." Marking them volatile makes the assignment atomic.
ThreadLocal & Publishing
ThreadLocal: Provides variables that can only be read/written by the same thread. Useful for storing user sessions or database connections to avoid synchronization.
Child Visibility: By default, no. However, if you use InheritableThreadLocal, the child thread receives a copy of the parent's value at the moment of creation.
Publishing an Object: This means making an object available to other threads (e.g., storing it in a public static field). Safe publication ensures the object is fully constructed before others see it, usually achieved via final fields, volatile, or synchronization.
Concurrency Hazards
Term 	Definition	Example
Race Condition	Result depends on the timing of thread execution.	Two threads doing count++ at the same time; some increments are lost.
Deadlock	Thread A waits for B, B waits for A. Neither can move.	T1 locks Key A, T2 locks Key B. T1 asks for Key B; T2 asks for Key A.
Livelock	Threads keep changing states in response to each other but make no progress.	Two people in a hallway trying to pass each other, both stepping side-to-side repeatedly.
Starvation	A thread is perpetually denied resources (CPU time).	A low-priority thread never runs because high-priority threads keep arriving.
The Executor Framework
Executors: A factory for creating thread pools (newFixedThreadPool, newCachedThreadPool).
Submit vs. Execute:
execute(): Part of Executor; used for "fire and forget" (returns void).
submit(): Part of ExecutorService; returns a Future so you can retrieve a result or handle exceptions.
Fork-Join / Phaser:
Fork-Join: Designed for work-stealing. Large tasks are split (fork) and results are combined (join).
Phaser: A more flexible version of CyclicBarrier and CountDownLatch. It allows a variable number of threads to wait on "phases" of execution.
RecursiveTask vs. RecursiveAction: Both are used in Fork-Join. RecursiveTask returns a value; RecursiveAction does not.
CompletableFuture (thenApply, thenCompose, thenAccept)
thenApply: Used for transformation. It takes a function and returns a result (like .map() in Streams).
thenCompose: Used for chaining. Use this when your transformation function also returns a CompletableFuture (prevents nested Futures).
thenAccept: Used for consumption. It takes the result but returns void (usually the end of the chain).
Advanced: Lock-Free & Utils
Lock-free Field Reassignment: You can use AtomicReferenceFieldUpdater. It allows you to perform an atomic CAS (Compare-And-Swap) on a specific field of an object without locking the whole object.
Utility Classes (java.util.concurrent.*):
CountDownLatch: One or more threads wait for N events.
CyclicBarrier: N threads wait for each other to reach a point.
Semaphore: Controls access to a shared resource using "permits."
BlockingQueue: Thread-safe queue (e.g., LinkedBlockingQueue) for Producer/Consumer patterns


