1. Generics & Parameterized Types
Parameterized/Generic Type: A type that allows you to specify a placeholder (like <T>) for the type of data it operates on. For example, List<String> tells the compiler this list only holds Strings.
Wildcard Parameterized Type (?): Represents an unknown type.
List<?>: A list of some unknown type.
List<? extends Number>: An unknown type that is a subclass of Number.
Can we add to List<?>? Generally, no (except for null). Because the compiler doesn't know what the specific type of the list is, it cannot guarantee type safety if you try to add a String to what might actually be a List<Integer>.
Generics in Exceptions: No, you cannot use parameterized types in exception handling (e.g., class MyException<T> extends Exception is illegal). This is because exception handling happens at runtime, but Java's generics are removed during compilation (Type Erasure).
2. Autoboxing
Autoboxing is the automatic conversion the Java compiler makes between primitive types (e.g., int) and their corresponding object wrapper classes (e.g., Integer).
Advantages: Cleaner code; allows primitives to be used in Collections (which only accept objects).
Pitfalls:
Performance: Creating thousands of wrapper objects in a loop can be slow and memory-intensive.
NullPointerExceptions: Unboxing a null wrapper object into a primitive results in a NullPointerException.
3. Enum Types
The "public static int" pattern (e.g., public static final int RED = 1;) had no type safety—you could accidentally pass the integer 1 where a "Color" was expected.
Problems Enums Solve:
Type Safety: You must pass the specific Enum type.
Namespace: Constants are grouped under the Enum name.
Functionality: Enums in Java are full classes; they can have fields, methods, and constructors.
4. Annotations
Annotations provide metadata about a program that is not part of the program itself.
Predefined Annotations:
@Override: Ensures a method is actually overriding a superclass method.
@Deprecated: Marks code as obsolete.
@SuppressWarnings: Tells the compiler to ignore specific warnings.
Custom Annotations: Created using @interface.
Retention Policy: Defines how long the annotation is kept.
SOURCE: Discarded by compiler.
