1. Memory Structure & Heap Division
How is virtual heap space divided?
Traditionally, the heap is divided into two main "generations" based on the Weak Generational Hypothesis (most objects die young):
Young Generation: Where new objects are allocated.
Eden Space: The first stop for most objects.
Survivor Spaces (S0 & S1): Objects that survive Eden move here.
Old Generation (Tenured): Objects that live long enough in the Young Gen are "promoted" here.
[!IMPORTANT]
Since Java 8, the PermGen (Permanent Generation) was replaced by Metaspace. While PermGen was part of the Java Heap, Metaspace is part of Native Memory.
PermGen vs. Metaspace (Java 8+)
PermGen (Java 7 and earlier): Had a fixed maximum size, leading to the infamous java.lang.OutOfMemoryError: PermGen space. It stored class metadata, static variables, and interned strings.
Metaspace (Java 8+): Stores class metadata in native memory. It can grow dynamically by default, making it much harder to run out of space for class loading.
