3. Objects and Copying
Java Object References
In Java, variables do not "hold" objects; they hold references (memory addresses) to objects on the heap. When you pass an object to a method, you are passing the reference by value.
Deep Copy vs. Shallow Copy
Shallow Copy: Copies the object, but the new object still refers to the same internal objects as the original.
Deep Copy: Creates a new object and recursively creates copies of every object it references. Changes to the deep copy do not affect the original.
Variable Shadowing
This occurs when a variable declared in a narrower scope (like a method parameter) has the same name as a variable in a broader scope (like a class field). The local variable "shadows" the field.
4. Garbage Collection (GC) Principles
How it works
GC identifies "unreachable" objects. It starts from GC Roots (Stack variables, static fields, JNI references) and follows the reference chain. Anything not reachable is eligible for collection.
GC Implementations
Serial: Single-threaded. Freezes the app ("Stop the World"). Good for small CLI tools.
Parallel: Multi-threaded for the Young Gen. Focuses on High Throughput.
CMS (Deprecated): Concurrent Mark Sweep. Tried to minimize pause times but suffered from fragmentation.
G1 (Garbage First): The modern default. Divides the heap into regions and collects those with the most garbage first to meet "pause time goals."
ZGC / Shenandoah: Ultra-low pause time collectors (sub-millisecond) designed for huge heaps.
Can you force GC?
No. You can call System.gc(), but this is only a hint to the JVM. The JVM can (and often does) ignore it. It is generally considered bad practice to rely on this in production code.
5. Monitoring & Performance
Disadvantages of a Very Large Heap
Long GC Pauses: If a "Full GC" occurs, the collector has more memory to scan, leading to longer application freezes.
OS Paging: If the heap exceeds physical RAM, the OS will swap to disk, destroying performance.
Utilities for JVM Monitoring
CLI: jstat (GC stats), j-stack (Thread dumps), j-map (Heap dumps), j-cmd.
GUI: VisualVM, JConsole, JDK Mission Control (JMC).
APM: Prometheus/Grafana (via Micrometer), New Relic, Datadog.
How to monitor GC behavior during execution?
Add these JVM flags to your startup command:
-Xlog:gc* (Modern Java)
-verbose:gc (Older Java)
6. Memory Model & Leaks
Memory Model (JMM)
Happens-Before: A formal guarantee that memory writes by one thread are visible to another (e.g., using volatile, synchronized, or final).
Atomicity: In Java, reads/writes to references and primitives (except long and double in some 32-bit VMs) are atomic. To ensure atomicity for logic, use AtomicInteger or synchronized.
What are Memory Leaks?
In Java, a leak happens when objects are no longer needed but are still referenced by a live object (e.g., a static Map that never stops growing). The GC cannot reclaim them because they are technically still "reachable."


