2. this vs. super
this: Refers to the current instance of the class. It’s used to resolve ambiguity between instance variables and parameters, or to call one constructor from another in the same class.
super: Refers to the parent (super) class. It’s used to access parent methods or variables that are overridden/hidden, or to call the parent’s constructor.
3. The equals() and hashCode() Contract
The rule is simple but critical for collections like HashMap or HashSet:
If a.equals(b) is true, then a.hashCode() must equal b.hashCode().
If a.hashCode() == b.hashCode(), a.equals(b) does not have to be true (this is called a collision).
If you override one, you must override the other.
