5. StringBuffer vs. StringBuilder
Both are used to create "modifiable" strings (unlike String which is immutable).
StringBuilder: Faster. It is not thread-safe (not synchronized). Use this for local variables or single-threaded logic.
StringBuffer: Slower. It is thread-safe (synchronized). Use this if multiple threads are modifying the same string.
6. Mutability vs. Immutability
Mutable: The state/data of the object can be changed after it is created (e.g., ArrayList, StringBuilder).
Immutable: The state of the object cannot be changed once initialized (e.g., String, Integer).
How to make a class immutable:
Declare the class as final (so it can't be extended).
Make all fields private and final.
Do not provide "setter" methods.
Initialize all fields via a constructor (performing a deep copy for mutable fields).
If the class has mutable fields (like a Date), return a copy in getters rather than the original reference (Defensive Copying).
Other Immutable Classes:
All Wrapper classes: Integer, Double, Long, Boolean, etc.
BigInteger and BigDecimal.
The Java 8 Date/Time API classes: LocalDate, LocalTime, ZonedDateTime.
7. Rules for equals()
To be "well-behaved," your equals() method must be:
Reflexive: x.equals(x) is true.
Symmetric: If x.equals(y), then y.equals(x).
Transitive: If x.equals(y) and y.equals(z), then x.equals(z).
Consistent: Repeated calls return the same result if no data changed.
Non-null: x.equals(null) must always be false.
8. Overriding vs. Overloading
Overloading: Same method name, different parameters (compile-time polymorphism). Happens within the same class.
Overriding: Same method name and same parameters in a subclass (run-time polymorphism). Uses the @Override annotation.
9. Replacing Multi-Inheritance
Java does not allow a class to extend more than one class to avoid the "Diamond Problem." We replace it using:
Interfaces: A class can implement multiple interfaces.
Composition: Instead of inheriting, your class holds an instance of another class and delegates work to it ("Has-a" vs. "Is-a").
Can an interface inherit from another? Yes! Use the extends keyword. An interface can even extend multiple interfaces: interface C extends A, B {}.
10. Regular vs. Static Initialization Blocks
Static Block: Runs once when the class is first loaded into memory. Used to initialize static variables.
Instance (Regular) Block: Runs every time an instance of the class is created, right before the constructor.


