3. Stack vs. Queue
Stack: Follows LIFO (Last-In, First-Out). Think of a stack of plates.
Queue: Follows FIFO (First-In, First-Out). Think of a line at a store.
4. TreeSet vs. TreeMap
TreeSet: Implements the Set interface (unique elements). It uses a TreeMap internally to store elements.
TreeMap: Implements the Map interface (key-value pairs).
Commonality: Both are backed by a Red-Black Tree, keeping elements/keys in sorted order.
5. HashMap Internal Structure & Collisions
A HashMap uses an array of "buckets." When you call .put(key, value):
The hashCode() of the key determines the bucket index.
If two different keys end up in the same bucket, a collision occurs.
Ways to Resolve Collisions:
Chaining: The bucket stores a linked list of entries. Since Java 8, if a bucket gets too full (8+ elements), the list converts to a Balanced Tree to improve performance from
