.
Open Addressing: (Used in other languages/logic) Finding the next empty slot in the array.
6. hashCode() & Performance
To achieve best performance (
 lookups):
Uniformity: The hash function should distribute keys evenly across buckets.
Consistency: The hashCode must not change as long as the information used in equals is not modified.
Contract: If a.equals(b), then a.hashCode() == b.hashCode().
7. Hashtable vs. ConcurrentHashMap
Hashtable: Ancient, legacy class. Every method is synchronized. It locks the entire table, making it very slow in multi-threaded environments.
ConcurrentHashMap: Modern and high-performance. It uses Lock Stripping (locking only specific segments or buckets) or CAS (Compare-And-Swap) operations, allowing multiple threads to read and write simultaneously without locking the whole map.
8. Special Versions of Collections
EnumSet / EnumMap: Extremely fast, bit-vector based collections designed specifically for Enums.
WeakHashMap: Entries are removed automatically when the key is no longer in ordinary use (helps prevent memory leaks).
IdentityHashMap: Compares keys using reference equality (==) instead of .equals().
9. Iterators & Modification
If you try to modify a collection (e.g., list.add()) while iterating over it with a standard Iterator, Java throws a ConcurrentModificationException. This is called a Fail-Fast iterator.
Safe Iterators (Fail-Safe):
CopyOnWriteArrayList / CopyOnWriteArraySet: These create a fresh copy of the underlying array whenever a mutation (add/set) occurs. The iterator works on the "old" snapshot of the data, so it never throws an exception, but it is memory-expensive for frequent writes.



