1. Data Structures & Java Nuances
Stack vs. Queue:
Stack (LIFO): In Java, avoid the Stack class (it's legacy and synchronized). Use Deque<T> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();.
Queue (FIFO): Use Queue<T> queue = new LinkedList<>();.
Heap: A complete binary tree where the parent is always smaller (Min-Heap) or larger (Max-Heap) than its children.
Java Implementation: PriorityQueue<T>.
Prefix/Suffix Trees (Tries): Excellent for autocomplete or DNA sequencing. Not in the standard library; usually implemented using a Map<Character, Node> at each node.
2. Boolean Operations & Short-Circuiting
Short-circuit (&&, ||): If the first operand determines the result, the second isn't evaluated.
Crucial for safety: if (obj != null && obj.isActive()) prevents NullPointerException.
Logical (&, |): Both sides are always evaluated. Rarely used for logic, mostly for bitwise manipulation.
