4. Trees, Graphs & Traversal
Self-Balanced Trees:
AVL: Strict balancing; faster lookups.
Red-Black: Looser balancing; faster insertions/deletions. Java’s TreeMap and HashMap (since Java 8) use Red-Black trees.
Graph Traversal:
BFS (Queue): Shortest path in unweighted graphs.
DFS (Stack/Recursion): Exhaustive search, topological sorting.
5. Recursion Types
Tail Recursion: The recursive call is the very last action. Note: Standard Java compilers (Javac) do not currently optimize for tail recursion (unlike Scala or Kotlin), so deep recursion can still cause StackOverflowError.
Mutual Recursion: Function A calls Function B, which calls Function A.
6. Problem-Solving Paradigms
Greedy: Makes the locally optimal choice at each step (e.g., Dijkstra’s, Prim’s).
Divide & Conquer: Splits problem into independent sub-problems (e.g., Merge Sort).
Dynamic Programming (DP): For overlapping sub-problems.
Top-down: Recursion + Memoization.
Bottom-up: Iteration + Tabulation.
Map/Reduce: Functional approach to processing data. Map transforms; Reduce aggregates.
7. System Design & Typing
Fixing Cyclic Dependencies:
Redesign: Extract the common logic into a third "mediator" class.
Setter Injection: (Spring) Inject dependencies after construction.
Lazy Loading: Use an ObjectProvider or a Proxy to resolve the dependency only when needed.

Static vs. Dynamic Typing:
Static (Java): Types checked at compile-time.
Dynamic (Python/JS): Types checked at runtime.
Duck Typing: "If it walks like a duck and quacks like a duck, it's a duck." In Java, this is partially mimicked using Reflections or Structural Typing in some modern JVM languages.


